      "rationale": "All six bench experiments used bovine blood with hematocrit 35 ± 2%, temperature 37 ± 0.5 °C, and inlet/outlet pressures measured by calibrated transducers. CFD boundary conditions were set to match measured values. Deviations in flow rate were less than 1.5% of set point. Test conditions are fully documented in the validation test report."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH values agree with measured NIH within 15% relative error across all validation test cases; RH < 1.0 for all cases.",
      "rationale": "Across all six validation experiments, relative error in predicted NIH ranged from 6.0% to 8.2%, well within the 15% acceptance threshold. RH values ranged from 0.87 to 0.93, all satisfying the RH < 1.0 criterion. Agreement is consistent across the six near-nominal test points, confirming model predictive capability at these conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "NIH and RH are demonstrated to be the primary QoIs governing the regulatory hemolysis acceptance decision for CPB devices.",
      "rationale": "NIH and the derived relative hemolysis index RH are the standard quantities used in FDA guidance and ISO 10993-4 for evaluating blood-contacting device hemolysis. The QoIs are directly linked to the regulatory decision criterion and are computed from the CFD shear-stress field using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same pump geometry, fluid, and operating conditions as the COU; any differences are documented and their impact assessed.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry identical to the COU device. Bovine blood was used as a surrogate for human blood, consistent with accepted practice. All six experiments were performed near the nominal CPB operating point of 4.5 L/min and 3000 RPM, which is representative of the primary clinical use scenario. The six data points cluster within a narrow band (4.2–4.8 L/min, 2950–3100 RPM), confirming relevance to the nominal COU condition. These results demonstrate that the model is validated for the full intended operating range of 2–7 L/min and 1500–4500 RPM, as the physics governing hemolysis are continuous and the model has shown consistent predictive accuracy at the nominal point.",
      "note": "WEAKENER TARGET: The rationale above extrapolates validation evidence from six tightly clustered near-nominal experiments (4.2–4.8 L/min, 2950–3100 RPM) to the full COU operating envelope (2–7 L/min, 1500–4500 RPM) without statistical coverage analysis, confidence intervals, or demonstration that model accuracy holds at the envelope boundaries."
